Quick Sort is a divide-and-conquer sorting algorithm.
Core idea:
  Pick a pivot element
  Partition the array so that:
  Elements smaller than pivot go to the left
  Elements larger than pivot go to the right
  Recursively apply the same steps to the left and right subarrays

  Choose a pivot
  Rearrange the array (partitioning)
  Pivot reaches its correct sorted position
  Recursively sort left and right parts

🔹 Why Quick Sort is Fast in Practice
    In-place (no extra array)
    Cache-friendly
    Very small constant factors
    Widely used in real systems

✔ Quick Sort is not stable
✔ It is in-place
✔ Pivot selection affects performance
✔ Partitioning is the heart of the algorithm

# arr = [4,6,2,5,7,9,1,3]
arr=[1,2]

def quick_sort(arr,low,high):
    if low<high:
        pIndex = fun(arr,low,high)
        quick_sort(arr,low,pIndex-1)
        quick_sort(arr,pIndex+1,high)

def fun(arr,low,high):
    pivot = arr[low]
    i = low
    j = high
    while i<j:
        while pivot>arr[i] and i<=high:
            i+=1
        while pivot<arr[j] and j>=low:
            j-=1
        if i<j:
            arr[i],arr[j]=arr[j],arr[i]
    return j
quick_sort(arr,0,len(arr)-1)
print(arr)

